{"title":"Using Custom Templates","markdown":{"yaml":{"title":"Using Custom Templates","author":"Template Guide","description":"How to use custom templates in your book"},"headingText":"Using Custom Templates","containsRefs":false,"markdown":"\n\n\nThis chapter demonstrates how to use custom templates to enhance your book's appearance and functionality.\n\n## Callout Boxes\n\nCallout boxes are a great way to highlight important information, warnings, or tips in your book.\n\n::: callout\ntitle: Information Callout\ntype: info\n\nThis is a standard information callout box. Use this for general information that you want to highlight.\n:::\n\n::: callout\ntitle: Warning Message\ntype: warning\n\nThis is a warning callout. Use this to warn readers about potential issues or things to watch out for.\n:::\n\n::: callout\ntitle: Danger Alert\ntype: danger\n\nThis is a danger callout. Use this for critical warnings or dangerous situations.\n:::\n\n::: callout\ntitle: Success Message\ntype: success\n\nThis is a success callout. Use this to highlight achievements or successful steps.\n:::\n\n## Enhanced Figures\n\nThe figure template provides a more attractive presentation for images with captions.\n\n::: figure\nsrc: ../images/img_7a214e28.png\ncaption: Enhanced Figure Example\ndescription: This figure uses the custom figure template to provide better styling and layout.\ncredit: Generated by DALL-E 3\n:::\n\n## Code Blocks\n\nThe code-block template enhances code display with titles and captions.\n\n::: code-block\ntitle: app.py\nlanguage: python\ncaption: Example Python function for calculating factorial\n\ndef factorial(n):\n    \"\"\"Calculate the factorial of n.\"\"\"\n    if n == 0 or n == 1:\n        return 1\n    else:\n        return n * factorial(n-1)\n        \n# Example usage\nresult = factorial(5)\nprint(f\"The factorial of 5 is {result}\")\n:::\n\n::: code-block\ntitle: styles.css\nlanguage: css\ncaption: CSS for a responsive button\n\n.button {\n  display: inline-block;\n  padding: 10px 20px;\n  background-color: #4CAF50;\n  color: white;\n  border-radius: 4px;\n  text-align: center;\n  transition: background-color 0.3s;\n}\n\n.button:hover {\n  background-color: #45a049;\n}\n:::\n\n## How Templates Work\n\nTemplates work by providing reusable HTML and LaTeX code that can be customized with parameters. To use a template:\n\n1. Define the template in your config.yaml file or as separate files in the templates directory\n2. Use the `:::` syntax in your Markdown to apply the template\n3. Provide parameters to customize the template's appearance\n\nThe template system supports both inline templates (defined directly in config.yaml) and file-based templates (stored in the templates directory). ","srcMarkdownNoYaml":"\n\n# Using Custom Templates\n\nThis chapter demonstrates how to use custom templates to enhance your book's appearance and functionality.\n\n## Callout Boxes\n\nCallout boxes are a great way to highlight important information, warnings, or tips in your book.\n\n::: callout\ntitle: Information Callout\ntype: info\n\nThis is a standard information callout box. Use this for general information that you want to highlight.\n:::\n\n::: callout\ntitle: Warning Message\ntype: warning\n\nThis is a warning callout. Use this to warn readers about potential issues or things to watch out for.\n:::\n\n::: callout\ntitle: Danger Alert\ntype: danger\n\nThis is a danger callout. Use this for critical warnings or dangerous situations.\n:::\n\n::: callout\ntitle: Success Message\ntype: success\n\nThis is a success callout. Use this to highlight achievements or successful steps.\n:::\n\n## Enhanced Figures\n\nThe figure template provides a more attractive presentation for images with captions.\n\n::: figure\nsrc: ../images/img_7a214e28.png\ncaption: Enhanced Figure Example\ndescription: This figure uses the custom figure template to provide better styling and layout.\ncredit: Generated by DALL-E 3\n:::\n\n## Code Blocks\n\nThe code-block template enhances code display with titles and captions.\n\n::: code-block\ntitle: app.py\nlanguage: python\ncaption: Example Python function for calculating factorial\n\ndef factorial(n):\n    \"\"\"Calculate the factorial of n.\"\"\"\n    if n == 0 or n == 1:\n        return 1\n    else:\n        return n * factorial(n-1)\n        \n# Example usage\nresult = factorial(5)\nprint(f\"The factorial of 5 is {result}\")\n:::\n\n::: code-block\ntitle: styles.css\nlanguage: css\ncaption: CSS for a responsive button\n\n.button {\n  display: inline-block;\n  padding: 10px 20px;\n  background-color: #4CAF50;\n  color: white;\n  border-radius: 4px;\n  text-align: center;\n  transition: background-color 0.3s;\n}\n\n.button:hover {\n  background-color: #45a049;\n}\n:::\n\n## How Templates Work\n\nTemplates work by providing reusable HTML and LaTeX code that can be customized with parameters. To use a template:\n\n1. Define the template in your config.yaml file or as separate files in the templates directory\n2. Use the `:::` syntax in your Markdown to apply the template\n3. Provide parameters to customize the template's appearance\n\nThe template system supports both inline templates (defined directly in config.yaml) and file-based templates (stored in the templates directory). "},"formats":{"html":{"identifier":{"display-name":"HTML","target-format":"html","base-format":"html"},"execute":{"fig-width":7,"fig-height":5,"fig-format":"retina","fig-dpi":96,"df-print":"default","error":false,"eval":true,"cache":null,"freeze":false,"echo":true,"output":true,"warning":true,"include":true,"keep-md":false,"keep-ipynb":false,"ipynb":null,"enabled":null,"daemon":null,"daemon-restart":false,"debug":false,"ipynb-filters":[],"ipynb-shell-interactivity":null,"plotly-connected":true,"engine":"markdown"},"render":{"keep-tex":false,"keep-typ":false,"keep-source":false,"keep-hidden":false,"prefer-html":false,"output-divs":true,"output-ext":"html","fig-align":"default","fig-pos":null,"fig-env